Controlling the Timeline – play, pause, reverse, restart

So far, you’ve learned how to create animations that run automatically when your page loads. But what if you want to be in the director’s chair - calling the shots? Play, pause, reverse, or even restart your animation whenever you want?

In this lesson, I’m going to show you exactly how to do that with GSAP’s powerful timeline controls.

Controlling Your Animation Timeline

Let’s create a timeline and add some animations:

Code Playground
import "./styles.css";
import gsap from "gsap";

// Create the timeline
const tl = gsap.timeline();

// Add tweens
tl.fromTo(".box", { x: -300 }, { x: 300, duration: 5 });

Result 

// Create the timeline
const tl = gsap.timeline();

// Add tweens
tl.fromTo(".box", { x: -300 }, { x: 300, duration: 5 }); // let's do a fromTo() animation and give a long duration so that we can notice different options

Now, you’ll see that when you refresh the page, these animations play automatically.

🎯 Goal: Let’s Take Control!

Instead of them playing automatically, let’s learn how to:

  • Play the timeline manually
  • Pause it
  • Reverse it
  • Restart it
Code Playground
import "./styles.css";
import gsap from "gsap";

// Create the timeline
const tl = gsap.timeline({ paused: true }); // Start in paused mode!

tl.fromTo(".box", { x: -300 }, { x: 300, duration: 5 });

// Button triggers
document.querySelector(".play-btn").addEventListener("click", () => tl.play());
document
.querySelector(".pause-btn")
.addEventListener("click", () => tl.pause());
document
.querySelector(".reverse-btn")
.addEventListener("click", () => tl.reverse());
document
.querySelector(".restart-btn")
.addEventListener("click", () => tl.restart());

Result

Let’s Build It Together

This will be our Html structure, we will add different buttons for different options 

<button class="play-btn">Play</button>
<button class="pause-btn">Pause</button>
<button class="reverse-btn">Reverse</button>
<button class="restart-btn">Restart</button>

Update your code:

// Create the timeline
const tl = gsap.timeline({ paused: true }); // Start in paused mode!

tl.fromTo(".box", { x: -300 }, { x: 300, duration: 5 });

// Button triggers
// The Play button triggers the timeline to start playing
document.querySelector(".play-btn").addEventListener("click", () => tl.play());
// The Pause button stops the animation right where it is:
document.querySelector(".pause-btn").addEventListener("click", () => tl.pause());
// The Reverse button plays the timeline backwards from the current position:
document.querySelector(".reverse-btn").addEventListener("click", () => tl.reverse());
// And the Restart button takes the timeline back to the start and plays it from the beginning:
document.querySelector(".restart-btn").addEventListener("click", () => tl.restart());

👉 Notice how we pass in { paused: true } - this means the animation won’t start playing immediately when the page loads. It will wait until we tell it to start.

Key Takeaways

Method Description
.play() Starts or resumes the animation from the current point.
.pause() Stops the animation where it is.
.reverse() Plays it backwards from the current point.
.restart() Starts the animation from the very beginning.

Wrap-Up & What’s Next

Awesome job! You now know how to control your animation timeline with GSAP’s .play(), .pause(), .reverse(), and .restart() methods. This is a powerful tool that will make your animations feel interactive and alive.

In the next lesson, we'll learn how to control timing and create smooth overlapping experiences!

What does the GSAP method do in a timeline?

Refer to the code below:

.pause()

A

Starts the timeline from the beginning.

B

Plays the timeline backward.

C

Pauses the timeline at its current position.

D

Resumes the timeline from the last played position.
